26LYvBe4c64.title: Great Smoky Mountains from North Carolina to Tennessee - The Ultimate Road Trip Adventure
26LYvBe4c64.description:
Thinking about planning a trip to the Great Smoky Mountains National Park and seeking serious fun and adventure for your road trip?  In this guide, we focus on the best things to do, eat, and stay on both sides of the Smokies.  We start off in North Carolina and end off in Tennessee.

Over the course of our 6 day Smoky Mountains itinerary, we were completely blown away and surprised that all that we could do.  This region has it all from thrills, nature's finest scenery, wildlife, unique stays, and fabulous restaurants.

aPTTsV20H5w.title: Is the Niagara Parks POWER STATION Worth It?  - Day vs. Night Show Experience
aPTTsV20H5w.description:
DID YOU HEAR? Niagara Falls has a new attraction and it's the Niagara Parks Power Station.  It's now open to the public with two ways to see this historic landmark.  

During the day, explore the generator floor on your own or in a guided tour.  See the scale of machinery, learn how they harnessed the power of the Horseshoe Falls, and learn the stories of the history and heritage.

At night, see the station come to life with Currents: Niagara's Power Transformed, an immersive multimedia show that will blow your socks off.  The technology they use reacts to where you are on the floor, lighting is projected all around you, the music score is riveting, and the story is captivating.

See a sneak peek of what the Niagara Parks Power Station is all about!

UPDATE:  The Tunnel at the Niagara Parks Power Station is opening July 1, 2022 so there's even MORE to see!

In partnership with Niagara Parks: https://www.niagaraparks.com/

CTC04LkHy1M.title: How to DIY Industrial Pipe Console Table With Basic Tools Only
CTC04LkHy1M.description:
Learn how to make your own DIY industrial pipe console table where the legs are finished in a matte black and topped with a beautiful walnut wood with a ton of grain character.  This is the step-by-step guide on improving your work from home set up and in my case, pairs perfectly with my standing desk.

MIND THE GAP - As part of the home office series, we left off with a big gap between the ergonofis Shift 2.0 standing desk and the wall so I needed to come up with something that would match the decor and be a useful part of the space.  This was the perfect solution albeit it took a lot of trial and error which you'll see in this tutorial video - everything from the galvanized steel tees, flanges, plumping pipes, and of course nipples.

🟢  CHAPTERS
0:00 - Intro
0:34 - How did we get here?
1:30 - Materials Needed
3:06 - Step 1 Cleaning
3:12 - Step 2 Assemble Legs
4:10 - Mistake #1
4:46 - Step 2 Redo
6:30 - Step 3 Spray Paint
7:35 - Step 4 Finish & Stain Wood
8:01 - Step 5 Assemble the Console
9:18 - Mistake #2
9:43 - Step 6 Set Up Console Table
10:25 - Mistake #3
10:43 - Step 6 New Width Console Table
11:24 - Outro

🛠 MATERIALS YOU NEED AND COST IN USD
As you saw, I had to make a lot of tweaks but here's the final collection of materials you need:
- 48" L 3/4" galvanized steel pipe ($18.60) - http://goaw.pl/3ai7xEF
- 24" L 3/4" galvanized steel pipe x 2 ($13.07) - http://goaw.pl/3j6mCNG
- 2" L 3/4" galvanized steel nipples x 2 ($1.97) - http://goaw.pl/36volqt
- 3/4" tee x 2 ($3.58) - http://goaw.pl/36t3Nz2
- 3/4" flange x 4 ($5.85) - http://goaw.pl/3alDyeT
- 1x8x6 pine wood ($11.79) - http://goaw.pl/3oAj4UM
- Black Spray Paint ($3.98) - http://goaw.pl/39Cfdm5
- Walnut Gel Stain ($20.52) - https://amzn.to/3r8qMay
- Pre-Stain ($5.48) - https://amzn.to/3coKElz
- Sand Paper ($13.99) - https://amzn.to/3aA7kgj 
- Polyurethane Spray ($7.96) - https://amzn.to/3rchHx8
TOTAL PRICE = $142.86 + tax if you need the staining equipment.

yqRurrlQ_4w.title: MagSafe Compatibility with Mobile by Peak Design | Something is very wrong...
yqRurrlQ_4w.description:
🔶 NEW COUPON CODE INSIDE: Go to https://goingawesomeplaces.com/peak-design and use code RESEARCH-vq4dQdYx6T to get $10 off any Peak Design Mobile case, mount, or accessory.

I started off this video wanting to show how Mobile by Peak Design is compatible with Apple MagSafe that was introduced with the iPhone 12.  Well, I managed to do that but more interestingly bizarre were some of the results I saw from my wireless charging tests using the Amperes 4 app.  

！MAGSAFE COMPATIBILITY
For the Peak Design fans out there, this is what you're really here for.  I think as you watch this video, you'll see that MagSafe just really isn't all that it's cracked up to be.  My honest opinion is that the MagSafe magnets themselves are just way too weak to be useful beyond the wireless charging use-case which in itself is pretty "weak".  This bodes well for Mobile by Peak Design because the whole point of this magnet system is to be able to interchange the docking of your case between all facets of your daily life from home to in the car, at the office, and when you're being active.  From my tests, MagSafe is 100% incapable of this.

⚠️ WHAT'S WRONG WITH MAGSAFE?
Take it for a grain of salt but I think the new wireless MagSafe charger doesn't work with non iPhone 12 phones.  I'm reading some scattered reports of others seeing the same thing.  I have no idea whether this is going to be fixable by iOS or if it's a hardware issue with the MagSafe charger.  I guess we'll find out soon as more tests roll in.

localized.title: MagSafe Compatibility with Mobile by Peak Design | Something is very wrong...
localized.description:
🔶 NEW COUPON CODE INSIDE: Go to https://goingawesomeplaces.com/peak-design and use code RESEARCH-vq4dQdYx6T to get $10 off any Peak Design Mobile case, mount, or accessory.

I started off this video wanting to show how Mobile by Peak Design is compatible with Apple MagSafe that was introduced with the iPhone 12.  Well, I managed to do that but more interestingly bizarre were some of the results I saw from my wireless charging tests using the Amperes 4 app.  

！MAGSAFE COMPATIBILITY
For the Peak Design fans out there, this is what you're really here for.  I think as you watch this video, you'll see that MagSafe just really isn't all that it's cracked up to be.  My honest opinion is that the MagSafe magnets themselves are just way too weak to be useful beyond the wireless charging use-case which in itself is pretty "weak".  This bodes well for Mobile by Peak Design because the whole point of this magnet system is to be able to interchange the docking of your case between all facets of your daily life from home to in the car, at the office, and when you're being active.  From my tests, MagSafe is 100% incapable of this.

⚠️ WHAT'S WRONG WITH MAGSAFE?
Take it for a grain of salt but I think the new wireless MagSafe charger doesn't work with non iPhone 12 phones.  I'm reading some scattered reports of others seeing the same thing.  I have no idea whether this is going to be fixable by iOS or if it's a hardware issue with the MagSafe charger.  I guess we'll find out soon as more tests roll in.

AiHKP-P0qk8.description:
I didn't know how useful quilts would be until I got these two - the Kammok Firebelly and Kammok Bobcat.  Each is rated for different temperatures and in this video find out why these down quilts are essential for almost any outdoor trip including camping, backpacking, or even at home.

Quilts are perfect for hammocks both as an overquilt and underquilt.  You'll also find it helpful to find out why these trail quilts make excellent great sleeping bags.  Find out how the button snaps make this happen, the technique of creating your own "toasty toebox", and how it is compatible with sleeping pads.

Fu-q-iMwKDA.title: Easy DIY Walnut Wood Shelves | Level Up Your Home Office
Fu-q-iMwKDA.description:
With many of you spending a lot more time working from home, it's time to level up your home office. This video breaks down the full step-by-step instructions on how to make your own wood shelves.  You'll quickly learn that DIY walnut wood shelves are a lot easier to do and just how easy and cheap it can be.

This is the first part of the Level Up Your Home Office series now that we're all spending a ton more time at home.  The shelve were a big part of the makeover and as someone with minimal wood working experience, I was surprised at how good this project turned out.  If I can do it, you guys can totally do it too!

🟧 Project Steps
0:00 - Intro
1:08 - Buying wood
2:05 - Buying stain and polyurethane
2:21 - Buying sandpaper
2:26 - Buying foam brush
2:33 - Tools used
3:49 - Weathering
4:27 - Sanding
5:39 - Pre-Stain
7:19 - Staining
9:07 - Second coating of stain
10:38 - Polyurethane semi-gloss coating
11:53 - Installing the shelves

🟢 Project Costs
Assuming you have a lot of the basics at home, here's everything else you'll need to buy:
- Black shelf brackets x 4 - $27.99 x 2
- Two 1x8x8 Knotty Pine boards - $15.99 x 2
- Minwax Gel Stain (Walnut) - $18.99
- Minwax Polyurethane (Semi-Gloss)  - $12.99
- Sandpaper 220 grit - $4.99
- Sandpaper 120 grit - $4.99
- Foam Brush - $3.49
TOTAL = $133.43 CAD

The cost may seem high but I found a similar designer shelf by West Elm (https://www.westelm.com/products/linear-wood-shelves-walnut-d7586/) which is $270 USD 2 foot (24") and 3 foot (36") shelf which is significantly shorter than the two lengths featured here (44" and 73") 

The main power tool you'll need for this project is a Finishing or Circular sander (https://goingawesomeplaces.com/makita-finishing-sander)

🔴 Black Shelf Brackets
I purchased these off of Amazon 
Canada (Black) - https://goingawesomeplaces.com/black-triangle-shelf-brackets
US (Gold) - https://goingawesomeplaces.com/gold-triangle-shelf-brackets

🔷 Feedback
Overall, this was super easy to do and I wanted to really show all the steps from buying to staining and mounting. I think the only part that was a little weird was the “weathering”. I don’t know if it’s absolutely necessary as all I managed to do was put in some dents and rough lines on the surface that you can barely notice so it’s a step you can totally skip.

EDMRbrlLiuY.description:

Watch this episode to learn how to avoid the Istanbul taxi scam, which hammam is the best for couples, where you can eat the best baklava in town, and of course highlights of mosques, cathedrals, and palaces.

qH545TpcFRQ.title: 16 Days in French Polynesia | Tahiti, Bora Bora, Rangiroa, and Fakarava
qH545TpcFRQ.description:
Watch the entire 16 day islands of Tahiti itinerary unfold where we started on Tahiti, explored the Papeete Market, lived in luxury at Le Meridien Bora Bora, experienced Rangiroa and Fakarava as locals, and did some of the most epic dives.  Open this up to learn more ↓

This journey to paradise starts from Toronto via San Francisco to Tahiti and follows us in linear order, how we planned our vacation through the islands, hopping to Bora Bora, Rangiroa, and then Fakarava before coming back to Tahiti with Air Tahiti.

This trip was possible because of our strategic use of points which included Aeroplan to get us to Tahiti with United Airlines and leveraging a mix of Marriott Bonvoy and Amex Membership Rewards to get our free stay at Le Meridien Bora Bora.

Enjoy our 2 week + 2 days vacation with authentic ukulele tracks recorded in French Polynesia.

4zP85vn7g3c.title: DAHABIYA Luxury Egypt Nile Cruise | You won't want to do the big river cruise ships after this
4zP85vn7g3c.description:
The big Nile cruise ships seem to be the most popular choice but the secret is something called a Dahabiya which is a sail boat that runs from Luxor to Aswan and vice versa that's 100 times better.  Watch to see a full walkthrough of the Dahabiya Loulia with Djed Egypt Travel and why this is the BEST way to do a river Nile cruise on your next trip to Egypt.  Open this up to learn more ↓

These are twin-mast sailing ships that are designed after the boats of the same name in the late 1800s and early 1900s when early explorers and archeologists were travelling up and down the Nile.  Djed Egypt Travel is the only company that has built these ships to evoke those memories with its design and decor while raising the level of cruising to modern day with small group sizes, all-inclusive Egyptian meals, comfortable cabins, delightful service, and dedicated Egyptologist.  

Ditch the big river Nile cruise ships for a bit of sailing where you can actually see what's on the Nile and enjoy it instead of zipping through in a metal box that's meant to keep you inside as opposed to walking local villages, discovering hidden petroglyphs, being at awe at an ancient sandstone quarry, and more importantly not being herded around like cattle.  

Ultimate the dahabiya Nile cruise is authentic, it's luxurious, and it'll be the best decision you make out of everything you plan for your trip to Egypt.  Hands down. 

In this video you'll also meet our Egyptologist, Abdulla Yosef from Djed Egypt Travel!

bbJ_ijdtesc.title: Things to do in NIAGARA FALLS including adventure, wine, and wait WAKEBOARDING?
bbJ_ijdtesc.description:
The Niagara region in Canada is home to so much more than Niagara Falls and I'm here to show you what you can see, do, eat, and stay over the course of a 3 day itinerary that's focused on not only the outdoors and adventure but also a few hidden gems perfect for couples as well. Open this up to learn more ↓

This video includes Niagara wineries, crazy wet jet boat tours a little bit too close to comfort to Niagara Falls, unexpected wake boarding experience, and amazing hiking that you'd never expect to find in the Niagara Region or Niagara on the Lake as a matter of fact.  Let's just say there's more to this part of Ontario than just Niagara Falls!

d6vXehPniI4.description:

Toyosu Fish Market is a massive complex and if it's your first time, it's easy to get turned around. More importantly, the tuna auction process is completely revamped for better or for worse.  Find out what the view from the Observation Windows look vs. Observation Deck, where the sushi restaurants are located, and the differences between all 3 buildings.  

Note that the Tsukiji Outer Market is still open so just keep that in mind when planning your trip to Tokyo.

r7bIHis2HwU.title: Top styles of RAMEN in Tokyo that you have to try
r7bIHis2HwU.description:
There are so many different styles of ramen in Tokyo which makes it tough to pick THE BEST but if you break it down by the best of each of these 5 types, you're going to get pretty close. I slurp through the city to find out that a bowl of ramen isn't just a bowl. Open this up to learn more ↓

🔷 THE RAMEN SERIES - TOKYO RAMEN GUIDE
After the tremendous success of last year's Must-Eat Restaurants in Tokyo, I knew I wanted to come back again but this time focus on a specific type of food and really go deep.  This is the second in the Ramen Tour Slurp Series about ramen.  Get hungry watching and start planning that trip to Japan!

🔰READ THE FULL GUIDE AND ACCESS THE MAP:  https://goingawesomeplaces.com/best-ramen-in-tokyo-japan/

🔰DO YOU KNOW YOUR RAMEN ETIQUETTE?
https://goingawesomeplaces.com/how-to-eat-ramen-in-japan-etiquette-rules

🍜 SLURP UP
0:30 - Hiroshi from Ramen Beast. Book your tour and down the app at http://ramenbeast.com
0:49 - Fuunji in Shinjuku
3:55 - Kikanbo in Kando
7:28 - Musashiya in Kichijoji
9:38 - Matador in Kita-senju
12:59 - Kagari in Ginza

So ultimately you're going to be thinking, which one is THE BEST?  Now that one's a hard one to answer but if I had to choose out of these 5, I have to give it up to Kikanbo for being just such a unique ramen experience that does it for me in terms of the ramen, the environment, and whole experience.  It's probably the most put together from a traveller perspective - they've really put some serious effort to make it friendly and ultimately creating a killer spicy miso bowl of ramen.

All opinions are my own of course!

Note that normally video is a sensitive topic as you're only allowed to photography the food but thanks to Ramen Beast's relationship with the ramen masters, we were allowed to film inside and behind the scenes.

💛Make sure to follow Hiroshi of Ramen Beast on IG at https://instagram.com/hshimakage

The best ramen in Tokyo is a tough one to choose from but if there's good indication of quality and ultimately deliciousness, it's the Michelin Guide and the Bib Gourmand. With the help of Ramen Beast, I share 3 epic ramen restaurants that are must-SLURP! Open this up to learn more ↓

🔷 THE RAMEN SERIES - TOKYO RAMEN GUIDE
After the tremendous success of last year's Must-Eat Restaurants in Tokyo, I knew I wanted to come back again but this time focus on a specific type of food and really go deep.  This is the first of many videos about ramen coming up on the channel so stay tuned!  We start off with those with either a Michelin Star or are recommended but there is of course so much more ramen to try.  

🔰READ THE FULL GUIDE AND ACCESS THE MAP:  https://goingawesomeplaces.com/best-ramen-in-tokyo-japan/

🔰DO YOU KNOW YOUR RAMEN ETIQUETTE?
https://goingawesomeplaces.com/how-to-eat-ramen-in-japan-etiquette-rules

🍜 SLURP UP
0:54 - Hiroshi from Ramen Beast. Book your tour and down the app at http://ramenbeast.com
1:25 - Toybox in Minowa (aka Remenya Toybox)
4:32 - Shichisai in Hacchobori near Tokyo Station
8:04 - Sobahouse Konjiki Hototogisu in Shinjuku

🇨🇦 Oh and YEP Toronto has its very own Konjiki.  Check them out here: https://konjikiramen.com/

Note that normally video is a sensitive topic as you're only allowed to photography the food but thanks to Ramen Beast's relationship with the ramen masters, we were allowed to film inside and behind the scenes.

xMoPDEljMLk.title: Flying Kiwi Behind the Scenes - New Zealand Outdoor Adventure Bus Tour
xMoPDEljMLk.description:
What is it like to be on a Flying Kiwi tour? I give the inside scoop on what to expect and from morning to night, a walkthrough of the Flying Kiwi New Zealand experience - the best New Zealand bus tour on the market that you probably never even heard of! Open this up to learn more ↓

I totally get it - as good as the tour companies are at describing their product, it's hard to get a real sense of what it's like to be on the tour.  That's why I focused on capturing what it's like to be on a Flying Kiwi Tour behind the scenes from the beginning of the day to the end of the day. 

The itinerary we were on was called REVERSE TRAVERSE and the collection of activities that you see are specific for that trip.  There are also other trips available such as the Ultimate Explorer which takes you around the entire country in 27 days.  Another thing to note is that while I mentioned that upgrades are available everyday, it's subject to availability and not all stops have cabin upgrade options.

c_2fd4lhcXk.title: How does the Ethiopian Airlines FREE TRANSIT HOTEL in Addis Ababa work? | Honeymoon VLOG 7
c_2fd4lhcXk.description:
It wasn't very clear to us before our trip how this Ethiopian Airlines free transit hotel business was going to work out for us from Cape Town - Addis Ababa - Seychelles so I wanted to share how it exactly works from start to end including the hotel voucher.  Open this up to learn more ↓

✈️TRAVEL HACKING
If you're travelling through Africa, Ethiopian Airlines is a very good option especially if you're with Star Alliance and using your points.  Often times, you'll run into issues with making connecting flights through Addis Ababa.  In our case, we arrived in Addis really late from Cape Town and to connect with our flight to Seychelles meant we had to stay overnight.  Luckily, Ethiopian Airlines offers a complimentary transit hotel if your layover is 8 to 24 hours and between two Ethiopian Airlines international flights..  

🔴The rules:
- You must be connecting through to an international flight on Ethiopian Airlines
- The long layover overnight must be the result of not having a choice for anything else (as in there are no options to fly out on the same day)
- Your passport must be eligible for a transit visa on arrival (most passports seem to be fine although there's no official list)

🔵 Here's what you need to know that nobody tells you about:
1️⃣ You CANNOT remove your bags during the transit so pack accordingly.  This was not made clear in other guides I've read.
2️⃣You do not need to go to the transfer office when you land.  Head straight out and go to the hotel transfer desk that is right outside the luggage hall in the arrivals area.
3️⃣Overnight in Ethiopia means that another country you fly to may immediately ask for Yellow Fever documentation.  It is recommended that you have this ready.

Are you planning a trip to Hamburg, Germany and don't know where to start, what to do, and where to stay? This travel guide will help you plan your itinerary here.  Open this up to learn more ↓

Over the years I've had a chance to explore a many number of regions of Germany including big cities and smaller towns but there's nothing quite like the experience I had in Hamburg.  What I experienced was something so profoundly exciting and energizing, I was completely blown away.  Hamburg is a city of contrasts - young and the classic, rivers for making money and others for spending money, red light districts juxtaposed against hipster neighbourhoods, and plenty of opportunities to party but also ways to chill out and relax.  The possibilities are endless in this maritime city!

Are you planning a trip to Hamburg, Germany and don't know where to start, what to do, and where to stay? This travel guide will help you plan your itinerary here.  Open this up to learn more ↓

Over the years I've had a chance to explore a many number of regions of Germany including big cities and smaller towns but there's nothing quite like the experience I had in Hamburg.  What I experienced was something so profoundly exciting and energizing, I was completely blown away.  Hamburg is a city of contrasts - young and the classic, rivers for making money and others for spending money, red light districts juxtaposed against hipster neighbourhoods, and plenty of opportunities to party but also ways to chill out and relax.  The possibilities are endless in this maritime city!

🔷 For the full guide that breaks out everything that you've seen in this video, head on to the blog post:  https://goingawesomeplaces.com/one-day-in-hamburg-what-to-see-do-eat-stay

CSAarOifcac.title: Adventure in CAPE TOWN - Sharks, Uthando, Surfing, & Hiking | Honeymoon VLOG 6
CSAarOifcac.description:
Cape Town sure did not disappoint with the slew of adventure and cultural activities that truly left us humbled.  From shark diving with Marine Dynamics to Surfing with Stoked School of Surf, Uthando South Africa in the townships, and hiking both Table Mountain and Lion's Head, we left Cape Town with all of our trip expectations met and then some.  Open this up to learn more ↓

🔴 Places Featured in this Vlog:
- 0:37 - Marine Dynamics (shark cage diving in Gaansbai)

- 6:08 - Uthando South Africa (visiting a township in Cape Town)
- 8:52 - The Company's Garden
- 9:14 - Bo-Kaap
- 9:25 - Table Mountain (attempt #1)
- 10:04 - V&A Waterfront + Victoria Wharf
- 10:18 - Stoked School of Surf (surfing classes in Muizenberg)
- 11:42 - Hang Ten in Muizenberg
- 11:56 - Table Mountain (success!)

8Zl6WAnZfiM.title: Adventure in the Ottawa Valley - Whitewater Rafting & Racetrack Speedway 🇨🇦
8Zl6WAnZfiM.description:
If you're looking for an adrenaline packed weekend from Toronto, look no further than the Ontario's Highlands and the Ottawa Valley.  Following my own Freedom Finder route, see how we conquered the whitewater rapids of the Ottawa River with OWL Rafting and drove ridiculously fast Mustangs and Lambos at Calabogie Motorsports Park.  Open this up to learn more ↓

🔴Here are all the spots featured here on the Freedom Finder Wandering Route:
Whitewater Brewing Company - 0:43
OWL Rafting - 1:20
Calabogie Peaks Resort - 3:44
The Valley Food & Drink Co. - 3:54
Calabogie Motosports Park - 4:19

Read all about my Freedom Finder Route in Ontario's Highlands: https://goingawesomeplaces.com/insane-adventure-ottawa-valley-ontarios-highlands-freedom-finder-route/

I've owned Apple Airpods for roughly 3 months and the Zolo Liberty Plus for 9 months.  I've used them on the road, at home, at coffee shops, and at the gym and I've gotten to know both really well.  Here's my feedback about each one for those that don't know which to grab or just want to know between the two which is better.

ETXdpuIQtVw.title: TOP 5 Dessert Spots in Tokyo, Japan You Have To Check Out (Watch This Before You Go)
ETXdpuIQtVw.description:
Here are my favourite 5 dessert shops in Tokyo, Japan that we visited on our recent trip. The Japanese love sweets and so it's worth it to try all the unique creations and fit it in between all the other restaurants that you'll be going to.  Everything from the croquant chou, soufflé pancake, matcha soft serve, ice cream, and crepes were all so good. 

The full guide is on the blog:  http://goingawesomeplaces.com/ultimate-tokyo-japan-food-guide-where-and-what-to-eat/

I don't know if it was just me but I found it hard to find good dessert recommendations in Tokyo.  There's so much of a focus on restaurants that the desserts often get overshadowed.  The other thing I noticed was that there was definitely a big affinity for European desserts.  Thing is, we didn't come to Japan for European pastries and so we were on the hunt for something more Japanese.  That's how I came to decide on these five places to eat dessert.

Here are all of the restaurants that are featured in this video:
1. Japanese Ice OUCA (食べログ) - 0:25
2. Flipper’s (代官山店) - 2:28
3. Zaku Zaku (ザクザク) - 4:11
4. Angels Heart - 6:12
5. Tsujiri (辻利) - 7:44

Ultimate Tokyo travel guide for food lovers that is packed with way more information and restaurants that you just gotta visit: http://goingawesomeplaces.com/ultimate-tokyo-japan-food-guide-where-and-what-to-eat/

QB8ma8-SpSk.title: 9 Must-Eat Restaurants in Tokyo, Japan (Watch This Before You Go)
QB8ma8-SpSk.description:
Get a complete rundown of all of my top restaurants I ate at on my latest trip to Tokyo (東京), Japan where you'll get a sneak peek of the mouthwatering food that we had and what you can expect when you come here as you plan your very own trip.  WARNING: Do not watch if already extremely hungry as it may result in hangry-ness.

The full guide is on the blog:  http://goingawesomeplaces.com/ultimate-tokyo-japan-food-guide-where-and-what-to-eat/

As one of the largest cities in the world and a super metropolis at that, there are over 160,000 restaurants to choose from.  With limited time in Tokyo, the challenge then becomes picking which ones to go to on your visit.  The other challenge is that there are also so many different types of food as well so you have to think strategically.  While I certainly didn't get even close to going to all the food spots we had planned, I was very happy with all the restaurants we went to.  What I've done is put together a top 9 list for all the amazing food we had and a behind the scenes look at why you should go and order.  

Here are all of the restaurants that are featured in this video:
1. Uoriki Kaisen Sushi (海鮮 魚力 渋谷東急東横店) - 0:20
2. Shin Udon (慎) - 2:12
3. Piss Alley/Memory Lane (Omoide Yokocho – 思い出横丁) - 4:06
4. Motodane (本種) - 5:36
5. Tempura Shinjuku Tsunahachi Ginza (天ぷら新宿つな八 銀座店) - 7:28
6. Tokyo Station Ramen Street – Rokurinsha Ramen (六厘舎) - 9:44
7. Nakaya (仲家) - 12:09

9. Sometaro Okonomiyaki (染太郎) - 16:05

2OZW3L3PcIY.title: MariCAR MAYHEM Through The Streets of Tokyo - Mario Kart Tokyo Bay BBQ Go Karts
2OZW3L3PcIY.description:
It's been a dream of mine to do the Mario Kart experience in Tokyo and on our latest trip, we made it happen.  We booked with the Tokyo Bay BBQ franchise specifically which leaves out of Koto district and their 2.5 to 3 hour drive called the K-L course around Rainbow Bridge, Tokyo Tower, Tokyo Gate Bridge, and Shibuya Crossing.

This video follows our entire experience from start to end where we dress up as our favourite Dragonball, Mario, Nintendo, Marvel, or Disney characters and drive through the streets of Tokyo on go karts. It's a crazy experience that is nuts that it's even legal but we had one heck of a time.

Make sure you get your international drivers license ahead of time at home.  The total cost for our trip was 12,000 JPY or roughly $108 USD.

💡 I purchased a multi-trip travel insurance policy before we left for our honeymoon and it was so easy with Kanetix.ca (Now RATESDOTCA).  Just punch in ⌨️  my requirements and bam 💥 it was there 🤯.  It was that easy.

5qZSe0ATTvw.title: An Allstar Tokyo Food Tour | Eating Like A Local With Arigato Japan Food Tours
5qZSe0ATTvw.description:
It's no secret that there are over 160,000 restaurants in Tokyo but one of the best ways I learned to explore the city like I local is through an ultra-local walking tour experience with a company called Arigato Japan Food Tours.  On this tour we got a chance to visit 5 different spots around the neighbourhoods of Yarakucho, Ginza, and Shimbashi where we tasted a brilliant selection of foods ranging from yakitori, katsu, gyoza, sashimi, waygu, and so much more.  I loved this way of eating because we got to try way more dishes than we ever could as a couple on the road in a single night.  Best part is we got to meet so many like-minded foodie travellers in our group that it was awesome to just chat and hang out.  Our local guide, Ryan, was also super knowledgable and passionate about Japanese food.

Check out Arigato Japan Food Tours and their full offering here: http://arigatojapan.co.jp/

For the particular tour that I went on, head over to: http://goingawesomeplaces.com/allstar-arigato-japan-food-tours

c210nEeTnH4.title: Tripped Up Movie World Premiere Behind the Scenes | Competitours Documentary
c210nEeTnH4.description:
In 2015, Sam and Will joined forces to create Team Awesome Duo for The Amazing Race-like trip called Competitours for a European vacation of a lifetime.  Unbeknownst to us, a film crew was following us all the way through, quietly documenting all of the craziness of travelling to mystery destinations, wild challenges, and red herrings.  2+ years later, the production team of Laura Watilo Blake, Robert (Bob) Reiland, and Fran Belkin put together a documentary that follows our adventures and tells a story of the mastermind of Steve Belkin and the bonds that are created throughout the trip.

While you'll have to wait a little longer for the movie to come out *crossing our fingers*, this gives you a look into what it was like to be at the world premiere of Tripped Up at the 42nd Cleveland International Film Festival as 7 of the 9 teams reunited for the first time as a group and watched a really good documentary that not only documents our whole trip but provides a sense of what it's like to be on Competitours, the drama along the way, and the bonds that were created that trumped the prize money.

44j_F4Kaacg.title: What It's Like to Safari at Kruger National Park in South Africa | A Travel Guide
44j_F4Kaacg.description:
While we were in Kruger National Park doing our self-drive safari, I took some time to film what it is like stay there and be your own navigator around the park to go wildlife watching.  Open this up to learn more ↓

This is meant to be a valuable resource especially for those that are first-timers.  This will help answer some pretty key questions that aren't limited to, what it's like to stay there, what are the camps like, do I need to cook, what kind of accommodations can I book, how the heck do you self-drive?  Let me do a walkthrough the world-famous safari nature park to help with your trip planning.

🔷Read the ultimate guide for planning a trip to Kruger: 
KRUGER GUIDE - https://goingawesomeplaces.com/kruger-national-park-guide-first-timers/
SAFARI GUIDE IN SA - https://goingawesomeplaces.com/best-way-to-safari-in-south-africa-in-kruger-national-park-and-private-game-reserve/


When I was planning my trip to South Africa and the safari component to our honeymoon, one thing that I've said before is that it was actually pretty challenging because there just isn't a lot of information out there about what it's actually like to be on a safari in Kruger National Park.  Sure there were blog posts about it but when it came to YouTube videos providing a walkthrough of the park, camp life, and self-drive, there just wasn't much out there.  Sure this video may not cover every single aspect of Kruger but for someone that stayed there for 3 nights and 4 days, it gives you a look into what our experience was like and the two of the larger camps we experienced - Skukuza and Lower Sabie.

qN4TqPPB3Cg.title: AMAZING & SCARY African Safari Self-Drive Experience at Kruger National Park | Honeymoon VLOG 4
qN4TqPPB3Cg.description:
Once we finished doing our loop around the Panorama Route, we entered the world-famous Kruger National Park from the Paul Kruger Gate and that started our 4 day 3 night epic adventure of self-drive.

Kruger was AMAZING because of all of the special moments we were able to witness whether it was in our SUV, driving around randomly or with one of the game drives run by the park itself.  Top 3 sightings have to be: 1) Baby elephant, 2) Hippo with all the turtles on back, and 3) Herd of water buffaloes crossing the road.

Kruger was also SCARY because of the lone huge cockroach that we saw in our first bungalow we stayed at in Skukuza.  In the video you'll see me recount the story of the night we checked in.  We unfortunately weren't able to catch it but resorted to using one of the towels to stuff the bottom of the bathroom door as that was the last place we saw it.  

I think one thing we kept asking ourselves while we were there was which experience we liked better.  The conclusion we came to was that doing self-drive is a VERY DIFFERENT experience.  While we loved how we were pampered at Elephant Plains and that they could go off-road to see the animals really up close, there was a bit more sense of adventure with Kruger because you were in control of what route you wanted to take everytime you went out.  Kruger being a massive park, there are definitely a lot more wildlife to spot and the type of terrain and landscapes very much over Sabi Sands which was more or less the same throughout.  Doing self-drive is also going to save you a lot more money over a private reserve even though Elephant Plains was quite affordable when comparing to others.  The issue with Kruger though is that you're not going to have the benefit of having a tracker to spot animals so a lot of times I felt like we would drive for hours and unless the animal was near the side of the road or if we saw a cluster of cars, it was very hard to spot anything far away.  

Lastly I think it'd be valuable to talk about the game drives offered by Kruger.  While it was nice to be on a guided trip while we were there, the experience was definitely subpar compared to the private reserve.  Instead of a truck of 9, we were on these massive trucks of 20+.  What was annoying about these trips is how frenzied it was when it came time to boarding the truck.  It's pretty much first come first serve so everyone swarms the trucks when its time to board the trucks because it sucks to be stuck in the back row sandwiched by other people.  Yes the vantage point is better but the rush for seats and the poorer quality guides/tracker was very apparently especially coming from a private game reserve.  

Love this video and want more?  Subscribe to get more from Going Awesome Places at http://goaw.pl/AwesomeTube

What was annoying about these trips is how frenzied it was when it came time to boarding the truck.  It's pretty much first come first serve so everyone swarms the trucks when its time to board the trucks because it sucks to be stuck in the back row sandwiched by other people.  Yes the vantage point is better but the rush for seats and the poorer quality guides/tracker was very apparently especially coming from a private game reserve.

YiKwgBGeeCA.title: Elephant Plains Review and Walkthrough of Game Lodge and Safari in Sabi Sands
YiKwgBGeeCA.description:
Let me take you on a tour of our game lodge, Elephant Plains in the Sabi Sands Game Reserve which is right next door to Kruger National Park.  This is an all-inclusive experience which has incredible accommodations (our Manyeleti Honeymoon Suite), all meals covered, 2 game drives and a bushwalk every day.  

When planning our honeymoon, I really didn't know what to expect even after booking this property.  It came as a recommendation and I'm so glad we ended up with Elephant Plains because not only was it an amazing experience, the price was also much more reasonable compared to other lodges we looked.  What really stands out for me is the friendly staff, our guide, tracker, the food, and ultimately how easy it was for us to spot the Big 5 and other animals throughout our 4 day/3 night safari experience.

Shoutouts go out to our guide Morné who was also gracious enough to allow me to interview him.  Our tracker, Dion and waiter Ishmael were also fabulous.  Nkomo!

49k6ZoCDVqY.title: Surviving the Colorado Altitude Snowboarding Vail and Breckenridge | VLOG5
49k6ZoCDVqY.description:
Over the weekend I flew down to Denver and met up with my two buddies Dany and Dave for our annual ski and snowboarding trip.  I've never been to the Rockies in these parts so was excited to see what it was all about.  Over the course of two days, we gave the resorts, Breckenridge and Vail a shot and here's a short on how it all went down.

The final verdict?  Breckenridge was NO MATCH for Vail.  It could have had something to do with the insanely cold day but loved Vail for its back bowls, open runs, and variety in terrain which made it a heck of a lot more interesting than the big wide open and easy runs at Breckenridge.  

The other thing we learned about going to Colorado is that the altitude there is not something to joke about.  I didn't think it'd have much effect but when you consider that the peak of these mountains surpasses 10,000 feet, you do feel the effects.  From tingly fingers, headaches, lungs working a lot harder, stomach feeling weird, super thirsty/dry and waking up in the middle of the night, I'd say it was serious-ish.  It wasn't as bad as doing the Inca Trail in Peru but it wasn't something you could laugh off.

This has perpetuated the need to carry dongles everywhere you go (HDML dongles, USB dongles, LAN dongles, SD card reader dongles...ALL THE DONGLES). From doing both the private reserve at Elephant Plains to self-drive in Kruger National Park to hopping over to Cape Town and enjoying everything that the Western Cape has to offer. eLN0nSMLvPI.title: HILARIOUS Tai Chi, Hot Springs, and Shrimp Fishing Day Trips from Taipei  | 12 Days in Taiwan EP5
eLN0nSMLvPI.description:
This is what happens when you try tai chi for the first time in Taipei.  We were completely out of our element at the temple but so amused with how clueless I'm sure we looked to the locals.  Right after we head to the town of Wulai just south of Taipei to finally soak ourselves in one of many hot springs in the area.  It was hot, cold, and sometimes just right but Yen Town was the perfect place to soothe our aching muscles.  If that wasn't enough, we wrapped up our day at a hip new place called Addiction Aquatic Development and then tried our hand at the favourite Taiwanese past-time of shrimp fishing.  

With a days left to go on our trip, we made sure to make it count making a fast-forward race to have Din Tai Fung for the famed xiao long bao and buy pineapple pastry/cake for friends and family back home.  

And just like that, our 12 days in Taiwan trip comes to a close.  I have to thank Joshua of MyTaiwanTour for this episode and introducing us to his tai chi class, and showing us Wulai.

qN1QuUUuEng.title: TRIBAL Hike in Taroko into the Mountains | 12 Days in Taiwan EP4
qN1QuUUuEng.description:
Episode 4 features our two day adventure hike in Taroko National Park which led us up various trails to eventually get to a homestay with Truku tribe member whom we call "Ah Ma".  Spitting with rain almost all the way through, the biggest challenge was coming back down but a little bit of perseverance and wobbly legs got us down to the Shakadang Trail.  As we learned later from our guide, Sam, this hike wasn't for beginners!

Of course an episode wouldn't be complete without some sort of train drama as we tried to get back to Taipei and of course more eating once we got there.

jAMYvOuhUDI.title: INJURED in Kenting and WEDGIE in Taitung | 12 Days in Taiwan EP3
jAMYvOuhUDI.description:
Episode 3 features highs of paragliding and soaring the skies of Taitung with a wedgie and also the lows of being pounded by waves in Kenting while attempting to surf and ALMOST dying (or at least being seriously injured) but regardless of it all we never lost our sense of adventure and we still filled our tummies with delicious food.

Heading south to Kenting and Taitung, there was one mission in mind and that was to explore by doing and in some ways we got more than we bargained for.  We combined our stay at Afei's hotel/inn/hostel with delicious meals there and also his personally run surfing trips. While we were brimming with confidence since South Africa, we totally weren't prepared for how hard it was out there with the big waves and challenging conditions.  We both came out with injuries.  Wanting to do something a little bit more laid back, we eventually got scooters, although that was a mission on its own.  In Taitung, we got to realize our dreams of paragliding although even that was very last minute.  On our very last day in the city, we borrowed bikes from our hotel and roamed through the city and as usual, managed to find great food places along the way.  

Taiwanese "re qing" was on display again in this travelogue with Sean whom we met at paragliding.  He totally didn't have to but he helped us find a cheaper way back home.  We also ended up having dinner together at the train station as we waited.  His story is actually quite amazing on its own as he was partway through his hike around the entire country with nothing more than his backpack.  His determination and strength was a true inspiration.   

⁉️ Ask A Local - Why Is Roots so Popular in Taiwan?
- You heard the receptionist's answer but seriously, why is Roots more popular in Taiwan than it is in Canada?

WgkZ7TM6Ol0.description:
Touching down in Taipei, the first episode follows Will on his adventures while based in Taipei.  Food is the primary mission on Day 1 as he eats through popular restaurants and a hyper local night market that should not be missed.  There was also the hike up to Xiangshan which had glorious views but led to some serious immobilizing leg cramps (HOW EMBARASSING!!!).  The second day featured a day trip with MyTaiwanTour to the famous Jiufen as the inspiration for Miyazaki's "Spirited Away" and Pingxi where sky lantern dreams are made of before finishing the day at the hyper touristy Shilin Night Market.

jEZ7tKA6rUg.title: Zolo/Soundcore Liberty+ Plus (by Anker) Total Wireless Earphones Unboxing and Hands-On Review
jEZ7tKA6rUg.description:
This is my complete and detailed review of the brand new Zolo Liberty+ (Liberty Plus) earphones that I purchased through their Kickstarter campaign.  As the first batch of users of these "total wireless earbuds", I've put together my personal thoughts on everything from the packaging through the unboxing, pairing, audio quality, functionality, physical design, fitment, battery life, and app.  There's a lot to delve into in this full review!

Zolo is a subsidiary company to Anker which is known for their mobile tech gadgets like power banks.  This is their first jump into serious audio gear and I like where they're headed towards and while I have been pretty impressed with these wireless earbuds, the final verdict as you'll see in the video is that it still needs a bit of polishing to truly delight.  It was just announced that they're rebranding to Soundcore so really these will be eventually called Soundcore Liberty Plus.

What I've Loved About Them:
- Sound is pretty damn good for what they are.  I think the only gripes I've had with them are songs with a lot of treble and high notes where they've sounded a bit flat.  Otherwise, pretty impressed.
- Battery life is really good TBH.  
- Simple pairing process and easy to connect once out of the case.  Single tap initiates BT connection and the iPhone picks it up really fast
- BT 5.0 - amazing range, and potential for multi-connectivity in the future I believe

What Needs Improving:
- The audio does cut out, particularly the left side.  It's random but usually involves long periods of listening.  The shortest period was maybe 30 minutes.  It'll cut but re-establish connection within a few seconds so it is tolerable
- I really wish there was a way to mod the charging case to allow for different tips.  Because my right ear uses the custom Sony ones, they stick out more and thus don't make good contact in the case.  Sometimes it'll lift out of the charging contacts while in my bag and turn on which inadvertently connects with my phone
- I’ve noticed that it has trouble with extreme highs  where it seems to clip off a bit. (Figured it out!  Shake to get the LEDs to light up)
- Charging case LEDs are still a bit of a mystery to me.  Sometimes they come on and sometimes they don't.  
- The app needs to look at what Jaybird has done and do what they did.  Custom EQ's please!!!
- Call audio outputs from the right ear only.  

Keep the comments coming in!  I want to know about your experiences and whether you're keeping them or not.  

If you're WILLing, you would be my new favourite person in the world subscribe to get more of WILL from Going Awesome Places :) http://goaw.pl/AwesomeTube

Zolo Liberty+ - Available on Amazon.com now: http://goingawesomeplaces.com/zolo-liberty-plus

Amazon.ca: http://goingawesomeplaces.com/zolo-liberty-plus-ca

If you're looking for the cheaper wireless earbuds, there's also the Zolo Liberty which are fully released:  http://goingawesomeplaces.com/zolo-liberty

rIKBLn3s4LQ.title: Spoiled at Elephant Plains in the Famous Sabi Sands Game Reserve | Honeymoon VLOG 2
rIKBLn3s4LQ.description:
Some say you should save the best for last but my goodness were we spoiled with ALL THE ANIMALS for our safari experience at Elephant Plains in the famed Sabi Sands Game Reserve just outside of Kruger National Park in South Africa.  Big 5?  No problem.  

I still can't believe how lucky we were out there for our 3 nights there.  Our guide and tracker for the whole trip was Morné and Dion who were phenomenal.  The food was absolutely delicious and our honeymoon suite (Manyeleti) was stunning. 

In this vlog watch how our 4 days unfolded from the drive up to Elephant Plains to the entire lodge experience.  See all the animals that we saw up close including:
- Lion (wait until 2:32 where we literally parked meters away from a male lion and listened to him roar into the night)
- Elephant
- Leopard
- White Rhino
- Buffalo
- Kudu
- Impala
- Giraffe
- Hyena
- Hippo
- Wild Dog

ya8DsZ9CL4Q.title: iPhone 8 vs X SUPER Extensive Review and Side By Side Comparison From The Real World
ya8DsZ9CL4Q.description:
I'm not holding anything back from this phone review.  With both Apple's iPhone 8 and X in my hands, I put together my longest review yet as I go through everything that makes the new iPhone X amazing, frustrating, and how is it better or worse than the iPhone 8 which only came out months earlier.  Specific areas I focus in are on the new tech features of the X (screen, Face ID, animoji, camera), hands on experience in the real world, a full battery test, side to side usage demonstrating differences, and food for thought from a travel blogger.  

Watch until the end (yes I can't believe I put together a video SO LONG) and find out ultimately what decision you should be making if you're having trouble picking between the iPhone 8 or the X.

Yes I know that toiletry organizers aren't exactly the most glamorous thing to be reviewing but as a traveller, these cases are pretty critical because they keep all of your daily use items together in the bathroom for easy retrieval, access, and organization.  Every toiletry organizer on the market is a unique but there are some key things that you need to look out for when you're looking to buy.  

I go through 3 of my toiletry organizers I've used over the past 10 years and why I like or dislike them.  I'll let you decide which one you might be interested in picking up.

d6pL6LyK1UU.description:
Have you been to a city so much where you just don't feel like doing the main touristy things and you just want to hang out, chowing down delicious food, video games, and a little shopping.  When you consider this is New York City, you never know what you'll stumble upon and of course I tried my best to avoid Times Square.

All the random things I did in 6 days in New York City:
- City Kitchen
- Shake Shack
- Food Emporium (to buy breakfast groceries)
- New York Public Library and the Rose Main Reading Room
- Adorama
- Ootoya
- Tim Ho Wan (THE Michelin starred dim sum specialists from Hong Kong)
- Ben's Cookies
- Forbidden Planet
- Learning how to make a Dutch Baby (recipe in the video)
- Madison Square Gardens
- The Kunjip
- Brooklyn Pilings
- Avoiding Times Square
- Sapporo
- Doughnut Plant

JomK8NGNCUo.title: COFFICES - 5 Awesome Coffee Shops in NYC For Working Remotely | VLOG3
JomK8NGNCUo.description:
Finding the perfect coffee shop that you can use as your office for remote work isn't easy to do and to do it in New York City is even trickier.  Yes there are a lot of coffee shops in NYC but not all of them are designed to be that perfect coffice.  In this feature, I visit 5 of my favourite coffee shops, interview the people that run them, and see for myself whether they stand to the test of being good coffices.

A good coffice is one where there's good wifi of course, there's plenty of seating and outlets to keep your electronics charged, the ambiance is somewhere that you can focus and get stuff done, the coffee has to be good, and because you'll be drinking a lot, there needs to be bathrooms as well!

fUzEZFgKm-g.title: Uber Airport Hacks To SAVE Money + Arriving in LaGuardia NYC | VLOG2
fUzEZFgKm-g.description:
As I make my way from Toronto to New York's LaGuardia, I test out for the very first time an Uber hack at the airport.  I had heard about it from an insider I know at Uber but had never done it.  See how I was able to get a ride from LGA to Midtown Manhattan for only $24.50 and also not have to pick up anyone along the way as part of Uber Pool.  CRAZY!!  Great way to start a trip :)

▶▶ How To Pay For LESS  When Taking An Uber From An Airport ◀◀
▪ Step 1:  If you have no wifi, make sure you get on it at the airport.  LGA has Boingo (boo Boingo) but they have a complimentary 30 minute pass so take advantage.
▪ Step 2:  Use Uber and set your destination.  The key now though is to set a pick up point that is just outside the airport.  
▪ Step 3:  Do a comparison of the prices between pick up right at the terminal or on a local street/hotel outside the airport.  If Uber Pool or Uber X is cheaper outside the airport, book it!
▪ Step 4:  Once you've been paired with a driver, call that driver right away.  Let him/her know that you are actually at the airport and to come grab you at the terminal.  You might have to negotiate where to pick you up depending on how strict the rules are at the airport.  The driver will typically oblige.
▪ Step 5:  Get whisked away to your destination and laugh at how much money you've saved!

Now that's what I call travelling smart :)

pC9Nwfchpds.title: Pistol Lake Eudae Minimalist Performance Henley and Sweat Shorts - Review from a Traveller
pC9Nwfchpds.description:
This is my full product review of Pistol Lake's Eudae Minimalist Performance Henley and Sweat Shorts.  I've been wearing their clothes for the past couple of months and I have to say that I am pretty impressed.  As travel gear, these are lightweight, moisture wicking, quick drying, incredibly soft to touch, easy to wash, and damn good looking.  There's something about their fabric that makes them really unique.  It's hard to describe even in the video but it is REALLY COMFY.  I love how it's not really branded either so it's the type of versatile clothing that you can wear with you every day for a dress-down set up or even in a more dress-up scenario when you pair it with a nicer pair of pants.  When it comes to travel clothing, it's versatility like this, comfort, and ease of wash which makes it a top choice when it comes to what is packed in your bag.  

Pistol Lake is a men's fashion focused on the ultra-functional minimalist with their special Eudae fabric which is made up of eucalyptus root and recycled bottles.  All of their clothing is made right in California too!

KTeyaM5uRKA.title: A Love Story 7 Years In The Making - Travel Themed Wedding Intro
KTeyaM5uRKA.description:
Inspired by Wong Fu, we created our very own love story video of that fateful day where Chantelle and I re-met on that direct flight from Toronto to Shanghai.  This film was used as the intro video after our parents and bridal party were introduced and prior to us making our entrance into the tent.  

Here's how the story goes.  Chantelle and I met when we were much younger in supplemental math class (think Kumon).  There wasn't much chemistry there as it was just an hour class and at most she asked me for my calculus answers.  University came and went and we didn't talk to each other.  It wasn't until a October 2010 day when my family and I were travelling to Shanghai for the Expo when I bumped into Chantelle on my flight.  You know there's always that flight attendant that checks your boarding pass before you walk in to let you know which aisle to walk down?  I walked aboard the plane, looked up, and I remember saying "Chantelle???".  We exchanged phone numbers and emails and the rest is, as they say, history!

This was a fun little project in the final month prior to our travel-themed wedding.  It's not exactly accurate but you get the idea :)

GNkvfpB_xVY.title: Why iPhone 8 Over Waiting for iPhone X and Full Unboxing - From A Traveller's Perspective
GNkvfpB_xVY.description:
A day before I get married, I receive a brand spankin' new iPhone 8 from Apple in Space Grey and in the 256GB capacity.  I'm friggin stoked because I'm coming from an iPhone 5S and 16GB just isn't enough.  In this video I talk about why I decided to jump the gun and purchase the iPhone 8 over the iPhone X which everyone is oogling about.  For the massive price differential, I'm not so convinced that it's worth it.  I have a few choices ahead of me.  Do I keep the 8 after the honeymoon or do I decide to sell and pick up the iPhone X afterwards?  

Hoping to produce more review videos of the iPhone 8 from a traveller's perspective soon so stay tuned for me so make sure you sub (especially for someone coming from a 5S!

Also...should I remove the plastic (totally should've gotten a screen protector ahead of time)?  Did I make the right decision?  Should I have waited for the iPhone X?

I need answers!!!  Drop a line below and let me know your thoughts :)

Hope you enjoyed my impromptu video...where I really should've been practicing my wedding speeches :O

1Xlec1cBObI.title: IRELAND - A Southern Roadtrip in 7 Days - Skellig Michael, Ring of Kerry, Cliffs of Moher, Galway
1Xlec1cBObI.description:
Join me as I take you on an epic 7 day roadtrip through the southern part of Ireland.  This travel guide explores the top attractions and best things to do that starts with a flight from Toronto to Dublin with Air Transat, down to Wicklow Mountains and the Glendalough Monastic City, Kilkenny, Rock of Cashel, Blarney Castle, Skellig Michael, Ring of Kerry, Kerry Cliffs, Killarney, Dingle Peninsula, Cliffs of Moher, Burren National Park, Galway, and then all the way back to Dublin.  

Throughout this trip, we learn the true meaning of Irish hospitality and the beauty of the dramatic countryside.  The lush green rolling hills filled with sheep contrasted against the jagged and sharp coastline made for one of the most incredible roadtrips I've ever done and that includes my trip to Iceland.  Skellig Michael is a must-do for lovers of puffins and Star Wars and is everything I dreamed of.  7 days was just enough to do this incredible loop but we came back wanting to see more.  My hope is that this'll show you that 7 days in Ireland is completely possible and to inspire you to embark on your own journey.

7 Day Itinerary in Southern Ireland | Ireland Travel Guide:  http://goingawesomeplaces.com/southern-ireland-ultimate-guide-7-day-road-trip-itinerary/

19) Coumenoole Beach (Dingle) - 04:13
20) Clogher Strand (Dingle) - 04:21
21) Gallarus Oratory (Dingle) - 04:33
22) Conor Pass (Dingle) - 04:36
23) Cliffs of Moher - 04:50
24) Burren National Park - 05:03

26) Galway - 05:23

m6a-b03Hn14.title: Nile Cruise Egypt - From the Dahabiya to Hurghada by the Red Sea
m6a-b03Hn14.description:
Unexpectedly my trip to Ethiopia led to a detour to Egypt and what a great decision it was.  Starting off with a luxurious Nile cruise in Egypt in our Dahabiya from Aswan to Luxor (Esna) followed by Indiana Jonesing in Luxor and then a relaxing few days to close out the trip in Hurghada by the Red Sea.  

Follow along my journey with this 4 minute montage of the highlights.  Without a doubt, the 3 nights aboard the 18th century two-masted boats was the best way to see Egypt.  It was an all-inclusive experience whereby the food was incredible and authentic, the cultural experience was top notch with the Egyptologist on hand to explain everything we saw and the boat that was authentically furnished cabins and a lounge worthy upper deck.   

In terms of Anceint Egyptian sites, we visited Kom Ombo Temple, Edfu Temple, and Gebel el Silsia sandstone quarry.

zk6t8_ihEcM.title: Ethiopia and the Omo Valley Experience - Raw Unseen Last Remaining Tribes
zk6t8_ihEcM.description:
Ethiopia's South Omo Valley is without a doubt one of the most culturally rich and diverse tribal regions in Africa.  Through this video you'll get a chance to see what it was like to be immersed in their culture, daily lives, and rituals.  It's a raw experience that you really won't find anywhere else.  

From the tribes of Hamar, Mursi, Kara, Dassenech, Ari, and Nyangatom you quickly realize that these are people that have been shielded from the modernization of the world. KJmhFdnQtM4.title: Via Ferrata del Diavolo - Competitours Amazing Race For Normal People | Episode 10
KJmhFdnQtM4.description:
Seriously who's heard of a Via Ferrata before?  It sounds insane to scale a mountain this way but it was something that had to be done during WW1 for Italian supply lines over the Alps.  With bolts hammered into the side of the mountain and tension wires we clipped our carabiners and was surprisingly not too difficult or vertigo inducing.  This was day 8 of Competitours.

📍PLACES FEATURED
Göschenen - 0:44

Q9bUoHN-OPI.title: Archery District - Archery Tag in Toronto
Q9bUoHN-OPI.description:
Get an inside look at what it's like to play the hottest activity in town - archery tag.  At Archery District in Scarborough, we played 10 vs. 10 archery for a full hour.  If you're looking for something different to do with your friends and want to try your hand at being Hunger Games' Katniss Everdeen, this is your chance!

Think dodgeball but instead of a ball you have a bow and arrow to tag the opponent on the other side out.  It's completely safe because the arrow tips are replaced with this giant foam marshmallow.  That being said, you'll still feel the impact when it hits you.  I was hit in the head but luckily we all had helmets.  Definitely a LOT less painful than paintball.

I will say that it's not easy.  Getting the hang of nocking and shooting an arrow while running around to avoid getting hit was a challenge.  You're also going to get pretty sweaty with the helmet.  

TIP:  Wear long sleeves if you can.  The kickback of the bow's string when you release an arrow gave a few of us red forearms after the game.  

▶ BLOG - http://goingawesomeplaces.com
▶ SUBSCRIBE - http://goaw.pl/AwesomeTube

Produced, filmed & edited by Will Tang

f1PqezXQjAs.description:

The crunching of ice.  Fog levitating over the St. Lawrence River.  A brisk blowing of arctic air swirling around.  The splashing of paddle on water.  Massive icebergs swiftly pass by.  Ice canoeing isn't for the faint of heart but that's what makes travel experiences truly memorable.

Check out the complete blog post about ice canoeing in Quebec City on the Going Awesome Places blog (http://goingawesomeplaces.com/extreme-ice-canoeing-quebec-city)

Z4OouD3aiAw.title: Royal Caribbean Quantum of the Seas - You Can Do That On A Cruise Ship?
Z4OouD3aiAw.description:
Get an inside look at what it's like to be on Royal Caribbean's newest cruise ship, Quantum of the Seas.  Touted as the world's first SMART ship, I was blown away by all the incredible experiences you can have on the ship that had me asking myself "Am I really doing this on a cruise ship?"

At this point, there's got to be some serious jaws dropped all around the cruising industry because Royal Caribbean has done it again with a ship so high-tech, innovative, entertaining, classy and just down-right fun that I'm sure the other cruise companies are scrambling to figure out how they can top it.  I'm not even sure how Royal Caribbean's going to top themselves.

For more details and photos, check out my blog post over at:  http://goingawesomeplaces.com/quantum-of-the-seas-never-thought-id-be-doing-that-on-a-cruise-ship

nYoFJKrC-vw.title: Travel Hack - Tangle Free Headphones
nYoFJKrC-vw.description:

So here's a trick I learned that I thought I'd share with you.  It was a quick video to put together and I hope you enjoy.

Mk5_6ma22Nc.title: Tokyo Tsukiji Fish Market Tuna Auction #2
Mk5_6ma22Nc.description:
Not everyone is able to make it up this early to get in line to then potentially have a chance to get into Tsukiji's live tuna auction.

This is the second live auction that happened while we were standing behind.  There are a lot of secret hand signals if you watch closely.  I was amazed at how fast it went.  Before we knew it, all the tuna on the ground were accounted for.

It's too bad they're moving the fish market to the suburbs.  This will surely be a missed tourist attraction of Tokyo.
